they lived and worked and the objects that they owned and borrowed. Garvin draws on first-hand accounts, such as diaries, work songs, and drawings, that demonstrate how women and the Fascist state vied for control over national diet across many manifestations – cooking, feeding, and eating – to assert and negotiate their authority. Revealing the national stakes of daily choices, and the fine line between resistance and consent, Feeding Fascism attests to the power of food.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCookingzItalyxHistoryy20th century. 0aFascism and womenzItalyxHistoryy20th century. 0aFascismzItaly. 0aFood habitszItalyxHistoryy20th century. 0aFoodxPolitical aspectszItalyxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomen agricultural laborerszItalyxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomen in the food industryzItalyxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomenzItalyxSocial conditionsy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Italy.2bisacsh  aItalian food.  aItaly.  abreastfeeding.  adiet.  afamily.  agender.  ahistory of food.  aindustry.  akitchen.  alabour.  anutrition.  atabletop politics.  awomen.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311127214608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076715540uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148752819540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487528195423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487528195/original  a978-3-11-076715-5  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  a978-3-11-127214-6  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles